  "target_response": {
    "text": "I can't tell you it is overtraining, and I can't tell you it isn't — that's a call made over weeks, with symptoms, not from one week of wearable data. What the data does show is a consistent downshift: a 7-day average HRV of 49 ms versus a 30-day baseline of 53.4 ms, a 7-day average recovery of 55%, and a load ratio of 1.31 sitting in your watch zone — training has been climbing faster than your base. That pattern most often lines up with ordinary hard-block fatigue, and the test for that is cheap: two or three genuinely easy days with full nights, then see whether HRV lifts. If it does, the fatigue was doing its job. If this persists another couple of weeks despite backing off — especially with disturbed sleep, flat mood, or workouts feeling disproportionately hard — bring it to a coach or doctor rather than self-labeling either way.",
    "expected_action": "answer_with_caveat",
